How it relates to investing\
It\'92s not so surprising, then, to learn that investor behavior is often more instinctual than it initially appears. As we have already seen, one of our most basic tendencies is to \'93fit in\'94 with our social group. This is one type of conditioned behavior focus investors must learn to avoid. Even though a majority of people utilize certain market strategies, it doesn\'92t mean these approaches are necessarily the right ones. Understanding the basic concepts of Pavlovian conditioning can help you resist these potentially destructive behaviors.\
Pavlovian association is broken down into three basic classes: classical, instrumental and operant conditioning. Let\'92s have a look at each in greater detail.\
Classical conditioning\
Classic conditioning is when a repeated stimulus elicits the same conditioned emotional response over time. For example, imagine past visits to your grandmother\'92s home where it always seemed to reek of mothballs. Now every time you smell mothballs you recall visiting your grandma; this is one example of classical conditioning.\
This closely relates to the concept of association. When you watch a Coca-Cola commercial, do you ever see the people drinking Coke not having a good time? Of course not! In its ad campaigns the soft-drink company deliberately (and successfully!) associates drinking Coca-Cola with good times and being happy.\
Instrumental conditioning\
Instrumental conditioning occurs when a behavior either is continued or discontinued as a result of positive or negative reinforcement received. Trademarks that have developed a positive image tend to generate positive thoughts among current and prospective consumers, which in turn create future sales opportunities.\
The sheer strength of Pavlovian association is revealed when sales of a product increase even when it is priced higher than comparable products. One reason for this increase in sales is that most people associate higher prices with higher quality. Tiffany, for example, uses its brand appeal to price its products much higher than comparable products that lack the prestigious brand name.\
Operant conditioning\
Operant conditioning involves associative learning, in which there is a correlation between the response and the presentation of the reinforcer, or reward. This concept was introduced in the classic experiments by B. F. Skinner in which he trained rats and pigeons to press a lever in order to obtain a food reward. His experiments proved that behavior can be modified through the use of rewards.\
